  "prompt": "How do you do \"inline if\" in JavaScript?",
  "response": "In JavaScript, you can use the conditional (ternary) operator to perform inline if-else logic. The syntax for the ternary operator is as follows:\n\n```javascript\ncondition ? expressionIfTrue : expressionIfFalse;\n```\n\nHere's a breakdown of the parts:\n\n- `condition`: This is the expression that evaluates to `true` or `false`.\n- `expressionIfTrue`: This is the expression that will be executed if the condition is `true`.\n- `expressionIfFalse`: This is the expression that will be executed if the condition is `false`.\n\nHere's an example:\n\n```javascript\nlet age = 20;\nlet canVote = (age >= 18) ? \"Yes, you can vote.\" : \"No, you cannot vote.\";\n\nconsole.log(canVote); // Output: \"Yes, you can vote.\"\n```\n\nIn this example, the condition is `age >= 18`. If `age` is 18 or older, `canVote` will be assigned the string `\"Yes, you can vote.\"`. Otherwise, it will be assigned the string `\"No, you cannot vote.\"`.",
